General Accidental Release Program:
This facility is constructed in accordance with appropriate mechanical and electrical codes for gas processing plants and is subject to OSHA?s PSM program.  Written programs and procedures  cover all of the key elements of the PSM program and the employees are well trained in the safe operation of this facility.

Chemical-Specific Prevention Steps:
The Kane plant includes the following safety features:
1.Hydrocarbon detectors with alarms;
2.Process safety relief valves;
3.Automated plant shutdown system (the plant will be automatically shutdown should key process variables vary from specified ranges);
4.Manual valves to permit isolation of various portions of the process;
5.Diking to contain liquid releases;
6.Appropriately placed fire extinguishers to combat incipient stage fires;
7.Excess flow valves on product storage;
8.Breakaway connections on product loading hoses to stop flow if a hose is pulled off;
9.Automated call-out system to notify plant operator(s) of abnormal operation.

Five Year Accident History:
The Kane Plant is scheduled to be placed in service in mid-late August, 2002.  This is a new facility and has not experienced any accidental releases that resulted in deaths, injuries, or significant property damage on  site or known offsite deaths, injuries, evacuations, sheltering in place, property damage or environmental damage.

Emergency Response Program Information:
The Kane Plant Emergency Response Plan has been coordinated with the McKean County Control Office.  The plan has been posted at the plant and all employees have been trained in the actions to be taken in the event of an emergency.

Planned Changes to Improve Safety:
No changes to the safety program or plant facilities are currently planned. However, weekly safety meetings are held during which incidents are reviewed, safety procedures discussed and changes proposed.  Our safety program is constantly improving.
